## 2 Notations and Preliminaries

**Notations.** We consider an undirected simple graph \(\mathcal{G}(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{E})\) where \(\mathcal{V}=\{1,2,\ldots,n\}\) and \(\mathcal{E}\subseteq\mathcal{V}\times\mathcal{V}\) with \(|\mathcal{E}|=m\) are the node and edge sets, respectively. The set of neighbors of \(v\) is denoted as \(\mathcal{N}(v)\subseteq\mathcal{V}\). The adjacency matrix \(\bm{A}\) of \(\mathcal{G}\) assigns unit weight \(a_{u,v}=1\) if \((u,v)\in\mathcal{E}\) and 0 otherwise. The \(v\)-th entry of the degree matrix \(\bm{D}\) is \(d_{v}=|\mathcal{N}(v)|\). Given \(\mathcal{S}\subseteq\mathcal{V}\), we define the volume of \(\mathcal{S}\) as \(\operatorname{vol}(\mathcal{S})\triangleq\sum_{v\in\mathcal{S}}d_{v}\). The support of \(\bm{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}\) is the set of nonzero indices \(\operatorname{supp}(\bm{x})\triangleq\{v:x_{v}\neq 0,v\in\mathcal{V}\}\). The eigendecomposition of \(\bm{D}^{-1/2}\bm{A}\bm{D}^{-1/2}=\bm{V}\bm{\Lambda}\bm{V}^{\top}\) where each column of \(\bm{V}\) is an eigenvector and \(\bm{\Lambda}=\operatorname{\mathbf{diag}}(\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2},\ldots, \lambda_{n})\) with \(1=\lambda_{1}\geq\lambda_{2}\geq\cdots\geq\lambda_{n}\geq-1\).

### Revisiting Anderson's APPR and its local runtime bound

We use \((\bm{p},\bm{z})\) for solving Equ. (1) while use \((\bm{x},\bm{r})\) for solving Equ. (3) or Equ. (4). With the initial setting \(\bm{p}\leftarrow\bm{0},\bm{z}\leftarrow\bm{e}_{s}\), APPR obtains a local estimate of \(\bm{\pi}\) denoted as \(\bm{p}\) by using a sequence of Push operations defined as

\[\boxed{\text{APPR}(\alpha,\epsilon,s,\mathcal{G}):\quad\text{\bf Repeat}\;(\bm{p}, \bm{z})\leftarrow\text{\tt Push}(u,\alpha,\bm{p},\bm{z})\;\text{\bf Until}\; \forall v,z_{v}<\epsilon d_{v};\;\;\text{\bf Return}\;\bm{p}.}\] (2)

At each repeat step \((\bm{p},\bm{z})\leftarrow\text{\tt Push}(u,\alpha,\bm{p},\bm{z})\), it synchronously updates both \(\bm{p}\) and residual \(\bm{z}\) whenever there exists an _active_ node \(u\in\mathcal{V}\) (a node with a large residual, i.e., \(z_{u}\geq\epsilon d_{u}\)). Specifically, for each active \(u\), it updates \(p_{u}\), \(z_{u}\), and \(z_{v}\) for \(v\in\mathcal{N}(u)\) by using a Push operator illustrated on the left. It stops when no active nodes are left. APPR can be implemented locally so that the runtime is independent of \(\mathcal{G}\). In particular, \(\operatorname{vol}(\operatorname{supp}(\bm{p}))\) is locally bounded, demonstrating the sparsity effect. We restate the existing main results as follows.

**Lemma 2.1** (Runtime bound of APPR [2]).: _Given \(\alpha\in(0,1)\) and the precision \(\epsilon\leq 1/d_{s}\) for node \(s\in\mathcal{V}\) with \(\bm{p}\leftarrow\bm{0},\bm{z}\leftarrow\bm{e}_{s}\) at the initial, \(\text{\tt APPR}(\alpha,\epsilon,s,\mathcal{G})\) defined in (2) returns an estimate \(\bm{p}\) of \(\bm{\pi}\). There exists a real implementation of (2) (e.g., Algo. 2) such that the runtime \(\mathcal{T}_{\text{APPR}}\) satisfies_

\[\mathcal{T}_{\text{APPR}}\leq\Theta\left(1/(\alpha\epsilon)\right).\]

_Furthermore, the estimate \(\hat{\bm{\pi}}:=\bm{p}\) satisfies \(\|\bm{D}^{-1}(\hat{\bm{\pi}}-\bm{\pi})\|_{\infty}\leq\epsilon\) and \(\operatorname{vol}(\operatorname{supp}(\hat{\bm{\pi}}))\leq 2/((1-\alpha)\epsilon)\)._

The main argument for proving Lemma 2.1 is critically based on: 1) \(\bm{z}\geq\bm{0}\) and \(\|\bm{z}\|_{1}\) decreases during the updates; 2) for each active \(u\), \(z_{u}\geq\epsilon d_{u}\), implying that \(\|\bm{z}\|_{1}\) is decreased by at least \(\alpha\epsilon d_{u}\), consecutively leading to \(\sum_{u}d_{u}\leq 1/(\alpha\epsilon)\).

### Problem reformulation

To approximate the PPR vector \(\bm{\pi}\), the original linear system in Equ. (1) can be reformulated as an equivalent symmetric version defined as

\[\bm{Q}\bm{x}=\bm{b},\quad\text{ with }\bm{Q}\triangleq\bm{I}-\tfrac{1-\alpha}{1+ \alpha}\bm{D}^{-1/2}\bm{A}\bm{D}^{-1/2}\text{ and }\bm{b}\triangleq\tfrac{2\alpha}{(1+\alpha)}\bm{D}^{-1/2}\bm{e}_{s},\] (3)

where again \(\bm{e}_{s}\) is the standard basis of \(s\), and \(\bm{Q}\) is a symmetric positive-definite \(M\)-matrix with all eigenvalues in \([\tfrac{2\alpha}{1+\alpha},\tfrac{2}{1+\alpha}]\). To solve Equ. (3) is equivalent to solving a quadratic problem

\[\bm{x}^{*}=\operatorname*{arg\,min}_{\bm{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}}\Big{\{}f(\bm{x} )\triangleq\frac{1}{2}\bm{x}^{\top}\bm{Q}\bm{x}-\bm{x}^{\top}\bm{b}\Big{\}},\] (4)

where \(f\) is strongly convex with condition number \(1/\alpha\). Indeed, Equ. (3) is a symmetrized version of Equ. (1) and has a unique solution \(\bm{x}^{*}=\bm{Q}^{-1}\bm{b}\). The PPR vector \(\bm{\pi}\) can be recovered from \(\bm{x}^{*}\) by \(\bm{\pi}=\bm{D}^{1/2}\bm{x}^{*}\). It is convenient to denote estimate of \(\bm{\pi}\) as \(\bm{\pi}^{(t)}\triangleq\bm{D}^{1/2}\bm{x}^{(t)}\). Given \(\bm{x}^{(t)}\), we define the residual \(\bm{r}^{(t)}\triangleq\bm{b}-\bm{Q}\bm{x}^{(t)}\). If \(\bm{x}^{(t)}\) is returned by a local solver for solving either Equ. (3) or Equ. (4), we then equivalently require \(\|\bm{D}^{-1/2}(\bm{x}^{(t)}-\bm{x}^{*})\|_{\infty}\leq\epsilon\). Hence, it is enough to have a stop condition \(\|\bm{D}^{-1/2}\bm{r}^{(t)}\|_{\infty}\leq 2\alpha\epsilon/(1+\alpha)\) for local solvers of Equ. (3) and Equ. (4).4

