\[\|\bm{r}^{(t)}\|_{2}\leq\frac{2}{(1+\alpha)\sqrt{d_{s}}}\left(\frac{1-\sqrt{ \alpha}}{1+\sqrt{\alpha}}+\epsilon_{t}\right)^{t},\]

_where \(\epsilon_{t}\) are small positive numbers with \(\lim_{t\to\infty}\epsilon_{t}=0\)._

Asymptotically, when \(\epsilon_{t}=o(\sqrt{\alpha})\), then the runtime of global LocSOR is \(\tilde{\mathcal{O}}(m/\sqrt{\alpha})\) where \(\tilde{\mathcal{O}}\) hides \(\log 1/\epsilon\). The main difficulty of analyzing the _optimal_ local LocSOR is that the nonnegativity and monotonicity of \(\bm{r}^{(t)}\) do not hold. Instead, by using a parameterized second-order difference equation, we develop new techniques based on the Chebyshev method detailed in Sec. 4.

### Parallelizable local gradient descent

One disadvantage of LocSOR is its limited potential for parallelization. The standard GD \(\bm{x}^{(t+1)}=\bm{x}^{(t)}-\bm{\nabla}f(\bm{x}^{(t)})\) (step size = 1), in contrast, is easy to parallelize across the coordinates of the update. Instead of updating \(\bm{r}\) and \(\bm{x}\) synchronously per-coordinate, we propose the following

\[\boxed{\bm{\Phi}_{\theta}\left(\mathcal{S}_{t},\bm{x}^{(t)},\bm{r}^{(t)}, \mathcal{A}=\texttt{LocSGD}\right):\;\bm{x}^{(t+1)}\leftarrow\bm{x}^{(t)}+ \bm{r}^{(t)}_{\mathcal{S}_{t}},\;\bm{r}^{(t+1)}\leftarrow\bm{r}^{(t)}-\bm{Q} \bm{r}^{(t)}_{\mathcal{S}_{t}}}\] (9)

Every coordinate in \(\mathcal{S}_{t}\) is updated in parallel at iteration \(t\). Interestingly, LocGD exhibits nonnegativity and monotonicity properties, and its runtime complexity is similar to that of LocSOR, as stated in the following theorem (To remind, \(\Delta_{i}=0\) for \(\overline{\gamma}_{T}\) of LocGD in Equ. (6) ).

**Theorem 3.5** (Runtime bound of LocGD).: _Given the configuration \(\theta=(\alpha,\epsilon,s,\mathcal{G})\) with \(\alpha\in(0,1)\) and \(\epsilon\leq 1/d_{s}\) and let \(\bm{r}^{(T)}\) and \(\bm{x}^{(T)}\) be returned by LocGD defined in (9) for solving Equ. (4). There exists a real implementation of (9) such that the runtime \(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{LocGD}}\) is bounded by_

\[\frac{1+\alpha}{2}\cdot\frac{\overline{\mathrm{vol}}(\mathcal{S}_{T})}{\alpha \overline{\gamma}_{T}}\left(1-\frac{\|\bm{D}^{1/2}\bm{r}^{(T)}\|_{1}}{\|\bm{D}^ {1/2}\bm{r}^{(0)}\|_{1}}\right)\leq\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{LocGD}}\leq\frac{1+ \alpha}{2}\cdot\min\left\{\frac{1}{\alpha\epsilon},\frac{\overline{\mathrm{vol} }(\mathcal{S}_{T})}{\alpha\overline{\gamma}_{T}}\ln\frac{C}{\epsilon}\right\},\]

_where \(C=(1+\alpha)/((1-\alpha)|\mathcal{I}_{T}|),\mathcal{I}_{T}=\mathrm{supp}(\bm{r }^{(T)})\). Furthermore, \(\overline{\mathrm{vol}}(\mathcal{S}_{T})/\overline{\gamma}_{T}\leq 1/\epsilon\) and the estimate \(\hat{\bm{\pi}}:=\bm{D}^{1/2}\bm{x}^{(T)}\) satisfies \(\|\bm{D}^{-1}(\hat{\bm{\pi}}-\bm{\pi})\|_{\infty}\leq\epsilon\)._

Note that \(\overline{\gamma}_{T}\) of LocGD is empirically smaller than that of LocSOR. Hence, LocGD is empirically slower than LocSOR by only a small constant factor (e.g., twice as slow), a finding consistent with observations of their standard counterparts [19]. Nonetheless, LocGD is much simpler and more amenable to parallelization on platforms such as GPUs compared to APPR.

