### Local Chebyshev method

Compared with GS and GD, the standard Chebyshev method offers optimal acceleration in solving Equ. (3). Following existing techniques (e.g., see d'Aspremont et al. [11]), we show there exists an upper runtime bound \(\tilde{\mathcal{O}}(m/\sqrt{\alpha})\) to meeting the stopping condition where \(\tilde{\mathcal{O}}\) hides \(\log 1/\epsilon\) (we presented it in Theorem C.6). Hence, the Chebyshev method is one of the optimal first-order linear solvers for solving Equ. (3). However, localizing Chebyshev poses greater challenges due to the additional momentum vector involved in updating \(\bm{x}^{(t)}\). Our key observation is that _if a substantial reduction in the magnitudes of \(\bm{r}^{(t)}\) is required within a subset of \(\mathcal{S}_{t}\), then the corresponding momentum coordinates are likely to possess significant acceleration energy_. Intuitively, a viable strategy involves localizing both the residual and momentum vectors. For \(t\geq 1\), denote the "momentum" vector as \(\bm{\Delta}^{(t)}:=\bm{x}^{(t)}-\bm{x}^{(t-1)}\) and \(\delta_{t:t+1}=\delta_{t}\delta_{t+1}\), we propose the localized Chebyshev as the following

\[\boxed{\begin{aligned} \bm{\Phi}_{\theta}\left(\mathcal{S}_{t},\bm{x}^ {(t)},\bm{r}^{(t)},\mathcal{A}=\textsc{LocCH}\right):\\ \hat{\bm{x}}^{(t)}\leftarrow(1+\delta_{t:t+1})\bm{r}^{(t)}_{ \mathcal{S}_{t}}+\delta_{t:t+1}\bm{\Delta}^{(t)}_{\mathcal{S}_{t}},\quad \delta_{t+1}=\left(2\frac{1+\alpha}{1-\alpha}-\delta_{t}\right)^{-1}\\ \bm{x}^{(t+1)}\leftarrow\bm{x}^{(t)}+\hat{\bm{x}}^{(t)},\quad\bm {r}^{(t+1)}\leftarrow\bm{r}^{(t)}-\hat{\bm{x}}^{(t)}+\frac{1-\alpha}{1+\alpha} \bm{W}\hat{\bm{x}}^{(t)},\end{aligned}}\] (10)

where \(t\geq 1\) with the initials \(\bm{x}^{(0)}=\bm{0},\bm{x}^{(1)}=\bm{r}^{(0)}\), \(\delta_{0}=0,\delta_{1}=(1-\alpha)/(1+\alpha)\), and \(\bm{W}=\bm{D}^{-1/2}\bm{A}\bm{D}^{-1/2}\) is normalized adjacency matrix. Our key strategy for analyzing (10) is to rewrite the updates of \(\bm{r}^{(t)}\) as a nonhomogeneous second-order difference equation (see details in Lemma C.8)

\[\bm{r}^{(t+1)}-2\delta_{t+1}\bm{W}\bm{r}^{(t)}+\delta_{t:t+1}\bm{r}^{(t-1)}= \sum_{j=0}^{t}\left((1+\delta_{j:j+1})\prod_{r=j+1}^{t}\delta_{r:r+1}\bm{Q} \bm{r}^{(j)}_{\mathcal{S}_{j,t}}\right),\] (11)

where we denote \(\mathcal{S}_{j,t}=\mathcal{S}_{j}\cap\cdot\cdot\cap\mathcal{S}_{t-1}\cap \overline{\mathcal{S}}_{t}\) given \(t\geq j\geq 0\) where \(\overline{\mathcal{S}}_{t}=\mathcal{V}\backslash\mathcal{S}_{t}\). In the rest, we define \(\tilde{\alpha}=(1-\sqrt{\alpha})/(1+\sqrt{\alpha})\) and recall the eigendecomposition of \(\bm{D}^{-1/2}\bm{A}\bm{D}^{-1/2}=\bm{V}\bm{\Lambda}\bm{V}^{\top}\). Based on the above Equ. (11), we have the following key lemma.

**Lemma 4.1**.: _Given \(t\geq 1,\bm{x}^{(0)}=\bm{0}\), \(\bm{x}^{(1)}=\bm{r}^{(0)}\). The residual \(\bm{r}^{(t)}\) of LocCH defined in (10) can be expressed as the following_

\[\bm{V}^{\top}\bm{r}^{(t)}=\delta_{1:t}\bm{Z}_{t}\bm{V}^{\top}\bm{r}^{(0)}+ \delta_{1:t}t\bm{u}_{0,t}+2\sum_{k=1}^{t-1}\delta_{k+1:t}(t-k)\bm{u}_{k,t},\]

_where \(\bm{Z}_{t}\) is a diagonal matrix such that \(\|\bm{Z}_{t}\|_{2}\leq 1\) and_

\[\bm{u}_{k,t}=\begin{cases}\sum_{j=1}^{t-1}\frac{\delta_{2:j}}{t}\bm{H}_{j,t} \left(\bm{I}-\frac{1-\alpha}{1+\alpha}\bm{\Lambda}\right)\bm{V}^{\top}\bm{r}^{ (0)}_{\mathcal{S}_{0,j}}&\text{ if }k=0\\ \sum_{j=k}^{t-1}\frac{\delta_{k+1:j}}{(t-k)}\bm{H}_{j,t}\left(\frac{1+\alpha}{ 1-\alpha}\bm{I}-\bm{\Lambda}\right)\bm{V}^{\top}\bm{r}^{(k)}_{\mathcal{S}_{k,j }}&\text{ if }k\geq 1,\end{cases}\]

_where \(\bm{H}_{k,t}\) is a diagonal matrix such that \(\|\bm{H}_{k,t}\|_{2}\leq t-k\)._

This key lemma essentially captures the process of residual reduction \(\bm{r}^{(t)}\) of LocCH. Specifically, given current iteration \(t\), we define the _running residual reduction rate_ for \(\bm{r}^{(k)}\) with \(k=0,1,2,\ldots,t-1\) of step \(t\) as \(\beta_{k,t}\), that is,

\[\beta_{k,t}\triangleq\frac{\|\bm{u}_{k,t}\|_{2}}{\|\bm{r}^{(k)}\|_{2}},\qquad \beta_{k}\triangleq\max_{t}\beta_{k,t}.\] (12)

Note that

\[\beta_{k,t}\leq\underbrace{\frac{2\|\bm{r}^{(k)}_{\overline{\mathcal{S}}_{k}} \|_{2}}{(1-\alpha)\|\bm{r}^{(k)}\|_{2}}}_{\approx\tilde{\mathcal{O}}(\epsilon)}+ \underbrace{\sum_{j=k+1}^{t-1}\frac{4\tilde{\alpha}^{j-k}(t-j)}{(1-\alpha)(t-k) -j}\frac{\|\bm{r}^{(k)}_{\mathcal{S}_{k,j}}\|_{2}}{\|\bm{r}^{(k)}\|_{2}}}_{ \leq\frac{\tilde{\gamma}_{k}}{(1-\alpha)(1-\tilde{\alpha})}},\]

where whether the last term can be even smaller depends on \(\|\bm{r}^{(k)}_{\mathcal{S}_{k,j}}\|_{2}\) for \(\mathcal{S}_{k,j}=\mathcal{S}_{k}\cap\cdot\cdot\cap\mathcal{S}_{j-1}\cap \overline{\mathcal{S}}_{j}\). However, we notice that the running geometric mean \(\overline{\beta}_{t}\triangleq(\prod_{j=0}^{t-1}(1+\beta_{j}))^{1/t}\) is even smaller in practice. Based on these observations and the assumption on \(\overline{\beta}_{t}\), we establish the following theorem.

**Theorem 4.2** (Runtime bound of LocCH).: _Given the configuration \(\theta=(\alpha,\epsilon,s,\mathcal{G})\) with \(\alpha\in(0,1)\) and \(\epsilon\leq 1/d_{s}\) and let \(\bm{r}^{(T)}\) and \(\bm{x}^{(T)}\) be returned by LocCH defined in (10) for solving Equ. (3). For \(t\geq 1\), the residual magnitude \(\|\bm{r}^{(t)}\|_{2}\) has the following convergence bound_

\[\|\bm{r}^{(t)}\|_{2}\leq\delta_{1:t}\prod_{j=0}^{t-1}(1+\beta_{j})y_{t},\]

_where \(y_{t}\) is a sequence of positive numbers solving \(y_{t+1}-2y_{t}+y_{t-1}/((1+\beta_{t-1})(1+\beta_{t}))=0\) with \(y_{0}=y_{1}=\|\bm{r}^{(0)}\|_{2}\). Suppose the geometric mean \(\overline{\beta}_{t}\triangleq(\prod_{j=0}^{t-1}(1+\beta_{j}))^{1/t}\) of \(\beta_{t}\) be such that \(\overline{\beta}_{t}=1+\frac{c\sqrt{\alpha}}{1-\sqrt{\alpha}}\) where \(c\in[0,2)\). There exists a real implementation of (10) such that the runtime \(\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{LocCH}}\) is bounded by_

\[\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{LocCH}}\leq\Theta\left(\frac{(1+\sqrt{\alpha})\overline{ \mathrm{vol}}(\mathcal{S}_{T})}{\sqrt{\alpha}(2-c)}\ln\frac{2y_{T}}{\epsilon} \right).\]

Golub & Overton [18] considered the approximate Chebyshev method by assuming that the inexact residual is sufficiently smaller than \(\epsilon\|\bm{r}^{(t)}\|_{2}\), where \(\epsilon\) must be small enough to ensure convergence. However, this assumption is overly stringent for our case. The novelty of our analysis lies in a more elegant treatment of a parameterized second-order difference equation, allowing us to circumvent this assumption. The nested APGD(\(\tilde{\epsilon}\)), namely ASPR proposed in Martinez-Rubio et al. [37] has runtime complexity \(\tilde{\mathcal{O}}(|\mathcal{S}^{*}|\widetilde{\mathrm{vol}}\left(\mathcal{ S}^{*}\right)/\sqrt{\alpha}+|\mathcal{S}^{*}|\operatorname{vol}\left( \mathcal{S}^{*}\right))\) where \(\mathcal{S}^{*}\) is the optimal support of \(\operatorname*{arg\,min}_{\bm{x}}\left\{f(\bm{x})+\epsilon\alpha\|\bm{D}^{1/2 }\bm{x}\|_{1}\right\}\) and \(\widetilde{\mathrm{vol}}(\mathcal{S}^{*})=\operatorname*{nnz}\left(\bm{Q}_{ \mathcal{S}^{*},\mathcal{S}^{*}}\right)\). Although it is difficult to compare our bound to this, one limitation of ASPR is that it assumes to call APGD(\(\tilde{\epsilon}\)) \(\mathcal{O}(|\mathcal{S}^{*}|)\) times to finish in the worst case. However, our iteration complexity is \(\tilde{\mathcal{O}}(1/(\sqrt{\alpha}(2-c)))\). Asymptotically, \(c=o(\sqrt{\alpha})\) (\(\epsilon\to 0\)), our complexity is \(\tilde{\mathcal{O}}(1/\sqrt{\alpha})\) could be better than \(\tilde{\mathcal{O}}(|\mathcal{S}^{*}|/\sqrt{\alpha})\). Fig. 3 presents a preliminary study on ASPR, indicating that it requires more operations than APPR.

We conclude our analysis by presenting a similar result for the local Heavy Ball (HB). Note the HB method is the one when \(\delta_{t}\delta_{t+1}\to\tilde{\alpha}^{2}\) where \(\tilde{\alpha}=(1-\sqrt{\alpha})/(1+\sqrt{\alpha})\). Hence, it has similar convergence analyses as to LocCH shown in Theorem D.8. The LocHB has the following updates

\[\begin{array}{|c|c|}\hline\bm{\Phi}\left(\mathcal{S}_{t};s,\epsilon,\alpha, \mathcal{G},\mathcal{A}=\textsc{LocHB}\right):\\ \hat{\bm{x}}^{(t)}\leftarrow(1+\tilde{\alpha}^{2})\bm{r}_{\mathcal{S}_{t}}^{( t)}+\tilde{\alpha}^{2}\bm{\Delta}_{\mathcal{S}_{t}}^{(t)}\\ \bm{x}^{(t+1)}\leftarrow\bm{x}^{(t)}+\hat{\bm{x}}^{(t)},\quad\bm{r}^{(t+1)} \leftarrow\bm{r}^{(t)}-\hat{\bm{x}}^{(t)}+\frac{1-\alpha}{1+\alpha}\bm{W}\hat{ \bm{x}}^{(t)}.\end{array}\] (13)

## 5 Generalization and Open Problems

Our framework can be applied to various local methods for large-scale linear systems. Extensions of this framework to other linear systems are detailed in Tab. 2 of Appendix E. More broadly, we consider the feasibility of local methods for solving \(\bm{Q}\bm{x}=\bm{b}\), where \(\bm{b}\) is a sparse vector (\(|\operatorname*{supp}(\bm{b})|\ll n\)) and \(\bm{Q}\) is a positive definite, graph-induced matrix with bounded eigenvalues. This leads us to question whether all standard iterative methods can be effectively localized, raising two key questions

1. Given a graph-induced matrix \(\bm{Q}\) and its spectral radius \(\rho(\bm{Q})<1\), a standard solver \(\mathcal{A}\), and the corresponding local evolving process \(\bm{\Phi}_{\theta}(\mathcal{S}_{t},\bm{x}^{(t)},\bm{r}^{(t)},\textsc{Loc} \mathcal{A})\), does a localized version of \(\mathcal{A}\) (over \(\mathcal{S}_{t}\)) converge and have local runtime bounds?
2. Based on current analysis, Theorem 4.2 relies on the geometric mean of residual reduction on \(\|\bm{r}^{(k)}\|_{2}\) being small. How feasible is acceleration within locality constraints? Specifically, a stronger bound could be established for solving Equ. (3) via LocHB and LocCH, with a graph-independent bound of \[\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{Loc}\mathcal{A}}=\Theta\left(\frac{\overline{\mathrm{vol} }(\mathcal{S}_{T})}{\sqrt{\alpha}\overline{\gamma}_{T}}\ln\frac{C}{\epsilon} \right),\text{ where }C\text{ a graph-independent constant.}\]

