### Proof of Lemma 2.1

**Lemma 2.1** (Runtime bound of APPR [2]).: _Given \(\alpha\in(0,1)\) and the precision \(\epsilon\leq 1/d_{s}\) for node \(s\in\mathcal{V}\) with \(\bm{p}\leftarrow\bm{0},\bm{z}\leftarrow\bm{e}_{s}\) at the initial, \(\operatorname{APPR}(\mathcal{G},\epsilon,\alpha,s)\) defined in (2) returns an estimate \(\bm{p}\) of \(\bm{\pi}\). There exists a real implementation of (2) (e.g., Algo. 2) such that the runtime \(\mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{APPR}}\) satisfies_

\[\mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{APPR}}\leq\Theta\left(1/(\alpha\epsilon)\right).\]

_Furthermore, the estimate \(\tilde{\bm{\pi}}:=\bm{p}\) satisfies \(\|\bm{D}^{-1}(\tilde{\bm{\pi}}-\bm{\pi})\|_{\infty}\leq\epsilon\) and \(\operatorname{vol}(\operatorname{supp}(\tilde{\bm{\pi}}))\leq 2/((1-\alpha)\epsilon)\)._

Proof.: To find an upper bound of \(\mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{APPR}}\), we add a time index for all active nodes \(u_{1},u_{2},\ldots,u_{t}\) processed in APPR of Algo. 2, a real implementation of (2). The parameter \(t\) is the number of active nodes processed, and \(u_{i}\) is the node dequeued at time \(i\). So, updates of \(\bm{p}\) and \(\bm{z}\) are from \((\bm{0},\bm{e}_{s})=(\bm{p}^{(0)},\bm{z}^{(0)})\) to \((\bm{p}^{(t)},\bm{z}^{(t)})\) as follows:

\[(\bm{p}^{(0)},\bm{z}^{(0)})\quad\xrightarrow{u_{1}}\quad(\bm{p}^{(1)},\bm{z}^ {(1)})\quad\xrightarrow{u_{2}}\quad(\bm{p}^{(2)},\bm{z}^{(2)})\quad\cdots \quad\xrightarrow{u_{t}}\quad(\bm{z}^{(t)},\bm{p}^{(t)}).\]

For each active \(u_{i}\), the updates of \((\bm{p},\bm{z})\) by definition can be represented as

\[\bm{p}^{(i)}=\bm{p}^{(i-1)}+\alpha z_{u_{i}}^{(i-1)}\cdot\bm{e}_{u_{i}},\quad \bm{z}^{(i)}=\bm{z}^{(i-1)}-\frac{(1+\alpha)z_{u_{i}}^{(i-1)}}{2}\bm{e}_{u_{i}} +\frac{(1-\alpha)z_{u_{i}}^{(i-1)}}{2}\bm{A}\bm{D}^{-1}\bm{e}_{u_{i}}.\]Since \(\bm{z}^{(0)}=\bm{e}_{s}\geq\bm{0}\), then \(\bm{z}^{(i)}\geq 0\) and \(\bm{p}^{(i)}\geq 0\) for all \(i\) by induction. Note that \(\|\bm{AD}^{-1}\bm{e}_{u_{i}}\|_{1}=1\), we have the following relation from the updates of \(\bm{z}\)

\[\|\bm{z}^{(i)}\|_{1}=\|\bm{z}^{(i-1)}\|_{1}-\alpha z_{u_{i}}^{(i-1)}\iff z_{u_{ i}}^{(i-1)}=\frac{\|\bm{z}^{(i-1)}\|_{1}-\|\bm{z}^{(i)}\|_{1}}{\alpha}.\]

Note \(\epsilon d_{u_{i}}\leq z_{u_{i}}^{(i-1)}\) for each active \(u_{i}\). Summing the above equation over \(i=1,2,\ldots,t\), we have

\[\sum_{i=1}^{t}\epsilon d_{u_{i}}\leq\sum_{i=1}^{t}z_{u_{i}}^{(i-1)}=\sum_{i=1 }^{t}\left(\frac{\|\bm{z}^{(i-1)}\|_{1}-\|\bm{z}^{(i)}\|_{1}}{\alpha}\right) =\frac{\|\bm{z}^{(0)}\|_{1}-\|\bm{z}^{(t)}\|_{1}}{\alpha}\leq\frac{\|\bm{z}^{( 0)}\|_{1}}{\alpha}=\frac{1}{\alpha},\]

where note \(\|\bm{z}^{(0)}\|_{1}=\|\bm{e}_{s}\|_{1}=1\) by the initial condition. Since \(\sum_{i=1}^{t}d_{u_{i}}\) exactly captures the number of operations needed, the runtime of Algo. 2 is then bounded as

\[\mathcal{T}_{\text{APPR}}=\Theta\left(\sum_{i=1}^{t}d_{u_{i}}\right)\leq\Theta \left(\frac{1}{\alpha\epsilon}\right).\]

To check the quality of estimate \(\bm{p}\), using the updates of \(\bm{p}^{(i)}\) and summing over all \(i\), we have

\[\bm{p}^{(t)}=\alpha\sum_{i=1}^{t}z_{u_{i}}^{(i-1)}\bm{e}_{u_{i}}=\underbrace{ \alpha\left(\frac{(1+\alpha)}{2}\bm{I}-\frac{(1-\alpha)}{2}\bm{AD}^{-1}\right) ^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^{t}\left(\bm{z}^{(i-1)}-\bm{z}^{(i)}\right)=\bm{\pi}-\bm{\Pi} \bm{z}^{(t)}},\]

where \(\bm{\Pi}\) is the PPR matrix. The above gives us \(\bm{\pi}-\bm{p}^{(t)}=\bm{\Pi}\cdot\bm{z}^{(t)}\). Since \(\mathcal{G}\) is undirected, the \(\bm{\Pi}\) matrix satisfies \(\pi_{v}[u]=(d_{u}/d_{v})\pi_{u}[v]\) where \(\pi_{v}[u]\) is the \(u\)-th element of PPR vector of sourcing node \(v\). Consider each \(u\)-th element of \(\bm{\Pi}\cdot\bm{z}^{(t)}\)

\[(\bm{\Pi}\cdot\bm{z}^{(t)})_{u}=\sum_{v\in\mathcal{V}}z_{v}^{(t)}\cdot\pi_{v} [u]=\sum_{v\in\mathcal{V}}z_{v}^{(t)}\cdot\frac{d_{u}}{d_{v}}\pi_{u}[v]\leq \epsilon d_{u}\sum_{v\in\mathcal{V}}\pi_{u}[v]=\epsilon d_{u},\]

where the last equality is due to \(\sum_{v\in\mathcal{V}}\pi_{u}[v]=1\). Hence, \((\bm{\pi}-\bm{p}^{(t)})_{u}=(\bm{\Pi}\cdot\bm{z}^{(t)})_{u}\leq\epsilon d_{u}\), which indicates \(\|\bm{D}^{-1}(\bm{p}^{(t)}-\bm{\pi})\|_{\infty}\leq\epsilon\). To see the bound of \(\operatorname{vol}(\operatorname{supp}(\bm{p}^{(t)}))\), note for any \(u\in\operatorname{supp}(\bm{p}^{(t)})\), it was an active node and there was at least \(\tilde{z}_{u}(1-\alpha)/2\) remain in \(u\)-th entry of \(\bm{z}^{(t)}\) where we denote \(\tilde{z}_{u}\) as the residual before the last push operation of node \(u\); hence

\[\sum_{u\in\operatorname{supp}(\bm{p})}d_{u}\leq\sum_{u\in\operatorname{supp}( \bm{p})}\frac{\tilde{z}_{u}}{\epsilon}=\sum_{u\in\operatorname{supp}(\bm{p})} \frac{\tilde{z}_{u}(1-\alpha)/2}{\epsilon(1-\alpha)/2}\leq\frac{\sum_{u\in \operatorname{supp}(\bm{p})}\tilde{z}_{u}^{(t)}}{\epsilon(1-\alpha)/2}\leq \frac{2}{(1-\alpha)\epsilon}.\]

Indeed, Lemma 2.1 is a special case of Theorem 1 in [2]. The proof outlined above adheres to the key strategy demonstrated in that theorem, which involves exploring the monotonicity and nonnegativity of \(\bm{z}\).

The real implementation of APPR, as shown in Algo. 2, presents a typical queue-based method. It has monotonic properties during the updates of \(\bm{p}\) and \(\bm{z}\) (Lines 10-16 of Algo. 2). It also holds element-wise that \(\bm{p}\geq 0\) and \(\bm{z}\geq 0\). The operations of \(\mathcal{Q}\).enqueue(\(u\)), \(\mathcal{Q}\).dequeue(), and \(v\notin\mathcal{Q}\) are all in \(\mathcal{O}(1)\). Line 4 to Line 5 is to design the marker for distinguishing between \(\mathcal{S}_{t}\) and \(\mathcal{S}_{t+1}\). If all active nodes are processed and no more active nodes are added into \(\mathcal{Q}\), then \(\mathcal{Q}\) will be empty, and finally, the algorithm returns an estimate \(\bm{p}\) of \(\bm{\pi}\).

