### Local Variant of GS-SOR and Proof of Lemma 3.2

The Gauss-Seidel Successive Over-Relaxation (GS-SOR) solver (see Section 11.2.7 of Golub & Van Loan [19]) for the linear system \(\bm{M}\bm{\pi}=\bm{s}\) via the following forward substitution

\[\textbf{for }i\textbf{ in }\mathcal{V}:=\{1,2,\ldots,n\}\textbf{ do}:\] \[p_{i}^{(t+1)} =\omega\left(s_{i}-\sum_{j=1}^{i-1}M_{ij}p_{j}^{(t+1)}-\sum_{j=i+ 1}^{n}M_{ij}p_{j}^{(t)}\right)/M_{ii}+(1-\omega)p_{i}^{(t)},\]

where \(\bm{p}\) is updated from \(\bm{p}^{(t)}\) to \(\bm{p}^{(t+1)}\). When the relaxation parameter \(\omega=1\), GS-SOR reduces to the standard GS method. Equivalently, let \(\Delta_{i}=(i-1)/n\) for \(i=1,2,\ldots,n\), then GS-SOR updates can be sequentially represented as

\[\textbf{for }i\textbf{ in }\mathcal{V}:=\{1,2,\ldots,n\}\textbf{ do}:\] \[\bm{p}^{(t+\Delta_{i+1})}\leftarrow\bm{p}^{(t+\Delta_{i})}+\frac{ \omega}{M_{ii}}\left(s_{i}-\sum_{j=1}^{i-1}M_{ij}p_{j}^{(t+\Delta_{i})}-\sum_{ j=i}^{n}M_{ij}p_{j}^{(t+\Delta_{i})}\right)\cdot\bm{e}_{i}.\]

Therefore, it is natural to define the following local variant of GS-SOR.

**Definition B.1** (Local variant of GS-SOR).: Consider the linear system \(\bm{M}\bm{\pi}=\bm{s}\). For \(t\geq 0\), we are given an active node set \(\mathcal{S}_{t}=\{u_{1},u_{2},\ldots,u_{|\mathcal{S}_{t}|}\}\) and let \(\Delta_{i}=(i-1)/|\mathcal{S}_{t}|\) for \(i=1,2,\ldots,|\mathcal{S}_{t}|\), providing \(\omega\in(0,2)\), it is natural to define the _local variant_ of GS-SOR as follows:

\[\textbf{for }u_{i}\textbf{ in }\mathcal{S}_{t}:=\{u_{1},u_{2},\ldots,u_{| \mathcal{S}_{t}|}\}\textbf{ do}:\] \[\textbf{p}^{(t+\Delta_{i+1})}\leftarrow\textbf{p}^{(t+\Delta_{i})}+ \frac{\omega}{M_{u_{i}u_{i}}}\left(s_{u_{i}}-\sum_{j=1}^{i-1}M_{u_{i}u_{j}}p_{ u_{j}}^{(t+\Delta_{i})}-\sum_{j=i}^{n}M_{u_{i}u_{j}}p_{u_{j}}^{(t+\Delta_{i})} \right)\cdot\bm{e}_{u_{i}},\] (15)

where \(\mathcal{S}_{t}\subseteq\mathcal{V}\). When \(\omega=1\) and \(\mathcal{S}_{t}=\mathcal{V}=\{1,2,\ldots,n\}\), it reduces to the standard GS.

We use the above definition to show APPR is a local variant of GS-SOR as the following.

